The new atoms API in v9 beta is not a drop-in replacement for controlled state, and the distinction matters in Angular and React apps alike.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

TanStack Table v9.0.0-beta.26 landed on July 1, 2026, carrying the same architectural bets that have been baking since the beta series began. Most of the conversation around v9 has focused on tree-shaking. The bundle size story is real. But the piece I keep watching teams get wrong is state management, specifically the new atoms API and when it replaces the v8 controlled-state pattern versus when it does not.
What v8 Controlled State Looked Like
This is the v8 pattern you almost certainly have in production:
// v8 controlled state (React)
const [sorting, setSorting] = useState<SortingState>([]);
const [pagination, setPagination] = useState<PaginationState>({
pageIndex: 0,
pageSize: 25,
});const table = useReactTable({
data,
columns,
state: { sorting, pagination },
onSortingChange: setSorting, // lifted to component state
onPaginationChange: setPagination, // same pattern
getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel(),
getSortedRowModel: getSortedRowModel(),
getPaginationRowModel: getPaginationRowModel(),
});
